{"id":"2104.03237","submitter":"Peng Ye","authors":"Hongchao Li and Peng Ye","title":"Renormalization group analysis on emergence of higher rank symmetry and\n  higher moment conservation","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Research 3, 043176 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevResearch.3.043176","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.quant-gas cond-mat.str-el hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Higher rank symmetry and higher moment conservation have been drawn\nconsiderable attention from, e.g., subdiffusive transport to fracton\ntopological order. In this paper, we perform a one-loop renormalization group\n(RG) analysis and show how these phenomena emerge at low energies. We consider\na $d$-dimensional model of interacting bosons of d components. At\nhigher-rank-symmetric points with conserved angular moments, the $a$-th bosons\nhave kinetic energy only along the $x^a$ direction. Therefore, the symmetric\npoints look highly anisotropic and fine-tuned. By studying RG in a wide\nvicinity of the symmetric points, we find that symmetry-disallowed kinetic\nterms tend to be irrelevant within the perturbative regime, which potentially\nleads to emergent higher-rank symmetry and higher-moment conservation at the\ndeep infrared limit. While non-perturbative analysis is called for in the\nfuture, by regarding higher-rank symmetry as an emergent phenomenon, the RG\nanalysis presented in this paper holds alternative promise for realizing\nhigher-rank symmetry and higher-moment conservation in experimentally\nachievable systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 7 Apr 2021 16:40:45 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 13 Dec 2021 16:43:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-14"}
